#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:7
# ded241bcfb7344f9910cbedadf465c78
msgid "Often one needs to create a map that can be printed or published. QGIS has a powerful tool called :guilabel:`Print Composer` that allows you to take your GIS layers and package them to create maps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:10
# 271c84b50d1c4343bea8f6ebcda4f115
msgid "Overview of the task"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:12
# 9da28434c90a4b2a912c019c81e9c3e2
msgid "The tutorial shows how to create a map of Japan with standard map elements like north arrow, scale bar, legend and label."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:15
# 530f90afd8574b15aa052da762f2106b
msgid "Get the data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:17
# b45f5bb6300f4d539c4980fd0a21eb05
msgid "We will use the Natural Earth dataset - specifically the Natural Earth Quick Start Kit that comes with beautifully styled global layers that can be loaded directly to QGIS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:19
# 2fa02d8022b34d58939761ca1edad0f1
msgid "Download the `Natural Earth Quickstart Kit <http://kelso.it/x/nequickstart>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:23
# 166d3d773d644dd588bcc9bc843e5fd1
msgid "Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:25
# 9b968ac817e04f9baec8710bb2d4a13a
msgid "Download and extract the Natural Earth Quick Start Kit data. Open QGIS. Click on :menuselection:`File --> Open Project`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:30
# 9349be4b113c4ceda39a322a4803b96a
msgid "Browse to the directory when you had extracted the natural earth data. You should see a file named :file:`Natural_Earth_quick_start_for_QGIS.qgs`. This is the project file that contains styled layers in QGIS Document format. Click :guilabel:`Open`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:35
# 498b72fad0ec4c98995df1f6578bcdf3
msgid "You would see a lot of layers in the table of content and a styled world map in the QGIS canvas. If you see errors displayed at the top of the canvas, click on the cross to close it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:40
# c714d8c65ddd4239b21562369843e742
msgid "In this tutorial, we will make a map of Japan. Click the :guilabel:`Zoom In` button and draw a rectangle around Japan to zoom to the area."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:45
# 0fd7e285f67a4ecc957c64e8601ee3ac
msgid "Once you are centered around the area of interest, click on the :guilabel:`New Print Composer` button. It is also accessible by :menuselection:`Project --> New Print Composer`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:50
# fb0fda8eb5194ff580f94eb73f91225a
msgid "You will be prompted to enter a title for the composer. Enter 'Japan map' and click :guilabel:`Ok`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:56
# ad37c6283c8c476cb63118c784e9e1da
msgid "In the Print Composer window, click on :guilabel:`Zoom full` to display the full extent of the Layout."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:61
# f0a1883d95b34f7d8374e776c8c7b8bf
msgid "Now we would have to bring the map view that we see in the QGIS Canvas to this layer. Click on the :guilabel:`Add Map` button. This tool can also be access from :menuselection:`Layout --> Add Map`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:67
# 9326dbadca064061b97a253b00fe918c
msgid "Once the :guilabel:`Add Map` button is active, hold the left mouse button and drag a rectangle where you want to insert the map."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:72
# c0a59319f9744f9bba1ca69d2f213e10
msgid "You will see that the rectangle window will be rendered with the map from the main QGIS canvas. Since we want our map to be covering the full extent of the layout, drag the corners of the rectangle to the edges."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:77
# 3ea6f2c1efb34a1a8e09413f045b5288
msgid "Let us adjust the zoom level for the given map. Click on the :guilabel:`Item Properties` tab and enter `3500000` for :guilabel:`Scale` value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:83
# 21fa9c95cd0e450d8b46bb965653917f
msgid "Now we will add a North Arrow to the map. Print Composer comes with a nice collection of map-related images - including many types of North Arrows. Click :menuselection:`Layout --> Add Image`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:88
# d86117e487d44aafaabf15453ef5366f
msgid "Holding your left mouse button, draw a rectangle on the top-right corner of the map canvas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:93
# d2649a8191254a41850639c422e58983
msgid "On the right-hand panel, click on the :guilabel:`Item Properties` tab and expand the :guilabel:`Search directories` section and select the North Arrow image of your liking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:98
# 42d29cfdf47349cea9053876e1310c6a
msgid "Next, scroll down below and un-check the :guilabel:`Background` option. This will make the image transparent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:104
# a2168d9496524a6082f2b401d7a04b6b
msgid "Now we will add a scale bar. Click on :menuselection:`Layout --> Add Scalebar`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:109
# b96b6dd212bf4195bf04174b00cb1c30
msgid "Click on the layout where you want the scalebar to appear. From the :guilabel:`Item Properties` tab, choose the Style that fit your requirement.  Also change the units to be :guilabel:`Map units` and label it 'Degree' since the map units are degress. You should also set the transparency by un-cecking the :guilabel:`Background` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:115
# 33e9f1580c054da6bc556687ed432011
msgid "Now we will add a legend to the map. Click on :menuselection:`Layout --> Add Legend`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:120
# 7bc1f555cb834792abaf64c913f3b2fe
msgid "Click on the layout where you want the legend to appear. Since our layer list is huge, you will see a big box with all the layers appear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:125
# 0cc5dbf26b09458a8d737a4cd7a326ab
msgid "Click on the :guilabel:`Item Properties` tab and select the layers which we do not want in the legend. Click the :guilabel:`-` button to remove it from the legend."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:130
# 0b46a32dc39443cf9d0cb9ed750e36f8
msgid "For the purpose of this map, we will keep legend information only for the five layers as seen below. Click on the :guilabel:`Edit` button and change the display text for the legend items to be more readable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:135
# 6b95a9d7849f47d0ada6539e912bae3d
msgid "Now time to label our map. Click on :menuselection:`Layout --> Add Label`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:140
# 0c861419a19f4a22b5b803bdf305a043
msgid "Click on the map and draw a box where the label should be. In the :guilabel:`Item Properties` tab, expand the :guilabel:`Label` section and enter the text. We can enter the text as HTML as well. Check the box :guilabel:`Render as Html` so the composer will interpret the HTML tags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:145
# be807da3c4d94eba8e7a6302ebdc9c4a
msgid "Once you are satisfied with the map, you can export it as Image, PDF or SVG. For this tutorial, letâ€™s export it as an image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/making_a_map.rst:150
# fcb238ebc64b46bc808417542484b99b
msgid "Save the image in the format of your liking. Below is the exported PNG image."
msgstr ""

